  "caption": "where should I eat in Tokyo when I go back in January?",
  "transcript": "Here are 20 must-eat spots when you visit Tokyo. Let me tell you why. Convenience stores, of course. 7-Eleven, Lawson, Family Mart. Tonkotsu, Marishichi for the biggest katsudan ever. Age 3 and their deep-fried sandwiches. I went Japanese sweet potato and, of course, egg salad. Sakapau was one of my favorite Italian meals ever. Mixing Italian dishes with Japanese ingredients and technique. Ichigaku, Tonkotsu, has cappuccino ramen, a name for the bubbles from re-emulsifying the broth. Kaiten Sushi Ginza Onodera for Kaiten Sushi. Chisokonya for a nicer spot, specializing in kaiseki cuisine. Tsugo was one of the best veggie meals I've ever had. Pizza Studio Tamaki is another Tokyo-style pizza must. I love that you can order smaller pies so you can try more. But Pizza Strata, I think, might have actually been better. Emo PB is a dessert shop with this creme brulee sweet potato and their sweet potato ice cream, which is actually a paste over vanilla ice cream and whipped cream. Yakitori Sei for an elevated Yakitori experience. Tokyo Curry Pond for this cheesy delight. Coffee Mameya Kokuru has a coffee omakase experience every coffee lover most book. Craving a bagel, check out new New York club bagel and sandwich shop. Mayan Sake for an incredible and unique sake pairing experience. Think a cheese-flavored sake to pair with risotto. American Cafe for these monster sandwiches. I got the hamburg and the egg salad. Yu Yorugi Urahara for a modern kaiseki omakase using only hyper-local ingredients.",
